---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/ui/TableOfContents';
import MethodologyCard from '../../components/ui/MethodologyCard.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-14",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What tools are needed to build a PC?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You only need a non-magnetic Phillips head screwdriver (sizes #1 and #2), a clean static-free workspace, and cable ties to organize your power wires."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Where do I connect the CPU cooler fan?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Plug the cooling fan cable into the CPU_FAN header on the motherboard. For liquid coolers, connect the pump cable to the dedicated AIO_PUMP or W_PUMP header to ensure constant power."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is dual-channel RAM configuration?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Dual-channel RAM links two memory channels together to double memory bandwidth. You must install your RAM sticks in slots A2 and B2 (slots 2 and 4) to activate this mode."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I avoid static electricity when building?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Build on a flat, non-conductive surface like a wooden table, avoid carpeted floors, and ground yourself regularly by touching a metal part of the PC case chassis."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="How to Build a PC 2026: Step-by-Step Assembly Guide — PSUCheck"
  description="The complete step-by-step guide to building a gaming or workstation PC in 2026. Learn assembly, component installation, and modular PSU wiring."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="calc-breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span aria-hidden="true" style="margin: 0 0.5rem; opacity: 0.5;">›</span>
        <a href="/guides/">Guides</a>
        <span aria-hidden="true" style="margin: 0 0.5rem; opacity: 0.5;">›</span>
        <span aria-current="page">How to Build a PC 2026</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <a href="/methodology" class="badge badge-safe" style="text-decoration:none;">✓ Sizing Methodology Verified</a>
          <span>Updated: July 14, 2026</span>
          <span style="margin: 0 0.5rem; opacity: 0.5;">•</span>
          <span class="reading-time-badge">12 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h1>How to Build a PC 2026: Step-by-Step Assembly Guide </h1>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <div class="adsense-placeholder" style="margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 1rem; border: 1px dashed var(--border-subtle); text-align: center; color: var(--text-tertiary); font-size: 0.75rem; border-radius: 4px;">
            ADVERTISEMENT — RECOMMENDED SPONSOR
          </div>

          <h2 id="intro">1. Introduction &amp; Context</h2>
          
  <p>Building a custom PC is one of the most rewarding projects you can undertake. It allows you to select the exact components to fit your performance needs, customize the aesthetics of your system, and understand how the hardware works together. While the process can seem intimidating for beginners, modern PC components are designed to assemble like high-tech LEGO bricks. This comprehensive step-by-step guide walks you through the entire assembly process.</p>
  <p>We cover motherboard preparation, CPU and cooler installation, case mounting, graphics card installation, and—critically—modular power supply wiring and cable management. Following this guide ensures a safe, successful build that posts on the first try. Read on to prepare your workspace, understand component clearances, and learn how to wire your system safely without risking electrical short circuits.</p>
  <p>Proper planning is essential for a smooth assembly. By organizing your tools, preparing your workspace, and routing your power cables systematically, you can avoid common building mistakes and protect your hardware investment.</p>
  

          <h2 id="section1">2. Technical Analysis &amp; Sizing Equations</h2>
          
  <p>Before you begin assembly, prepare a clean, well-lit workspace. You will need a non-magnetic Phillips head screwdriver (sizes #1 and #2), a small bowl to organize screws, and a flat anti-static surface like a wooden table. We recommend grounding yourself regularly by touching a metal object (like your case chassis) to discharge static electricity. Avoid building on carpeted floors, which can accumulate static charge.</p>
  <p>Start by preparing the motherboard outside of the case on top of its cardboard box. First, install the CPU into the socket, paying close attention to the alignment indicators (such as the small triangle in the corner). Lower the retention arm to lock the processor in place. Next, install your M.2 NVMe SSDs into their slots and lock them down. Finally, insert your RAM DIMM modules into slots A2 and B2 (the second and fourth slots from the CPU socket) until they click securely. Motherboard layouts require slots A2 and B2 for dual-channel stability.</p>
  <p>Once these primary components are installed, mount the CPU cooler brackets. If using an AIO liquid cooler, install the backplate now, as it is much easier to attach before mounting the motherboard inside the chassis shroud.</p>
  

          <div class="adsense-placeholder" style="margin: 1.5rem 0; padding: 1rem; border: 1px dashed var(--border-subtle); text-align: center; color: var(--text-tertiary); font-size: 0.75rem; border-radius: 4px;">
            ADVERTISEMENT — IN-CONTENT BANNER
          </div>

          <h2 id="section2">3. Detailed Architecture, Rails &amp; Standards</h2>
          
  <p>With the motherboard prepared, install the CPU cooler. If using an air tower, mount the backplate and mounting brackets, apply a pea-sized amount of thermal paste to the CPU, and screw down the cooling block. If using an AIO liquid cooler, install the radiator in the case first (typically at the top or front panel as an intake), then mount the CPU block. Ensure the radiator pump is positioned lower than the highest point of the loop to prevent air bubbles from gathering in the pump housing.</p>
  <p>Next, prepare the case. Install the motherboard standoffs, insert the motherboard's rear I/O shield (if not integrated), and slide the motherboard into the chassis, securing it with standoffs screws. Route the case's front panel cables (USB, Audio, Power Switch) to their motherboard headers before installing larger components, keeping the cabling clean.</p>
  <p>Additionally, plan your case fan layout. We recommend a balanced or slightly positive pressure configuration, with intake fans at the front and bottom, and exhaust fans at the rear and top. This layout ensures constant fresh air flow and minimizes dust accumulation.</p>
  

          <h2 id="section3">4. Sizing Guides &amp; Real-World Recommendations</h2>
          
  <p>Now, install the power supply. Unbox your modular PSU, connect only the required cables (ATX 24-pin, EPS 8-pin CPU, PCIe GPU cables), and slide the PSU into its shroud at the bottom of the case. Route the cables through the routing grommets to the motherboard connectors. Connect the 24-pin motherboard power and 8-pin CPU power runs, ensuring they click into place. Modular layouts simplify routing and improve case aesthetics.</p>
  <p>Finally, install the graphics card. Remove the case expansion slot covers, align the GPU with the primary PCIe x16 slot, and press down until it clicks. Secure it with bracket screws. Connect the power cables—using a native ATX 3.1 12V-2x6 cable for modern GPUs, or separate PCIe 8-pin runs. Double-check all connections, plug in the monitor to the GPU, connect the power cord, and power on your system.</p>
  <p>Once the system boots, enter the BIOS to verify that all components are detected correctly. Enable XMP or EXPO to configure your RAM to its rated speeds, and adjust fan speed profiles for optimal cooling and quiet operation before installing your operating system.</p>
  

          <h2 id="section4">5. Verdict &amp; Long-Term Total Cost of Ownership (TCO)</h2>
          
  <p>In conclusion, building a PC requires patience, attention to detail, and proper planning. By following these step-by-step instructions, preparing your motherboard first, and routing your modular power supply cables cleanly, you can assemble a safe, stable, and highly performant custom PC. Take your time, double-check all connections, and enjoy the reward of booting your new system.</p>
  <p>By monitoring system stability, maintaining clean dust filters, and applying appropriate technical knowledge during component upgrades, you can ensure a successful build and enjoy years of reliable performance.</p>
  

          <h2 id="faq">6. Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
          <h3>What tools are needed to build a PC?</h3><p>You only need a non-magnetic Phillips head screwdriver (sizes #1 and #2), a clean static-free workspace, and cable ties to organize your power wires.</p>
<h3>Where do I connect the CPU cooler fan?</h3><p>Plug the cooling fan cable into the CPU_FAN header on the motherboard. For liquid coolers, connect the pump cable to the dedicated AIO_PUMP or W_PUMP header to ensure constant power.</p>
<h3>What is dual-channel RAM configuration?</h3><p>Dual-channel RAM links two memory channels together to double memory bandwidth. You must install your RAM sticks in slots A2 and B2 (slots 2 and 4) to activate this mode.</p>
<h3>How do I avoid static electricity when building?</h3><p>Build on a flat, non-conductive surface like a wooden table, avoid carpeted floors, and ground yourself regularly by touching a metal part of the PC case chassis.</p>
          <div class="related-guides" style="margin-top:2rem;padding:1.5rem;background:var(--surface-card);border-radius:8px;border:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
            <h3 style="margin-top:0;">Related Tools</h3>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="/build-plan">Build Blueprint Generator</a> — Generate a printable, step-by-step build plan with compatibility checks and PSU analysis for your specific components.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <TableOfContents client:load />
          <MethodologyCard />
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

